# Git standards (mandatory)

All branch names, commit messages, PR titles, and CI/workflow event names must be in **English**.
UI copy for the product stays Spanish (es-CO); Git metadata is English only.

## Branches

Format: `<type>/<short-kebab-description>`

Allowed `type` values:
- `feature` — new capability
- `fix` — bug fix
- `chore` — tooling, config, deps
- `docs` — documentation only
- `refactor` — no behavior change
- `hotfix` — urgent production fix
- `ci` — pipelines / Actions

Rules:
- Lowercase kebab-case only (`a-z`, `0-9`, `-`)
- No spaces, accents, or Spanish words
- Keep short and specific

```text
✅ feature/mandatory-labels
✅ fix/preview-debounce
❌ feature/etiquetas-obligatorias
❌ EtiquetasObligatorias
```

## Commits (Conventional Commits)

Format: `<type>(optional-scope): <imperative summary>`

Allowed `type` values: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `build`, `ci`, `chore`, `revert`

Rules:
- Subject in English, imperative mood (“add”, not “added” / “adds”)
- No trailing period
- Aim for ≤72 characters on the subject line
- Body (optional) explains **why**, wrapped at ~72 chars
- One logical change per commit when practical
- Never commit secrets (`.env`, keys, passwords)

```text
✅ feat(builder): add mandatory label fields to Datos block
✅ chore: add git standards cursor rule
❌ feat: agregué etiquetas obligatorias
❌ Updated stuff.
```

## Pull requests & events

- PR title: same Conventional Commits style as the subject
- PR description in English (Summary + Test plan)
- GitHub Actions workflow `name:` and job ids in English
- Do not force-push `main`
- Prefer merge via PR; delete the branch after merge

## Agent behavior

When creating branches, commits, or PR text in this repo, follow this rule automatically.
If a proposed name/message is not in English or not conventional, rewrite it before applying.
